🧠 OS Concept 1: Threads
1️⃣ Simple Idea

A thread is the smallest unit of execution inside a process.

👉 Process = big container
👉 Threads = workers inside it

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Think of a restaurant 🍽️

Restaurant = Process

Waiters = Threads

All waiters:

work independently

but share same kitchen & resources

⚙️ Why Threads Exist

Problem with processes:

❌ Heavy (more memory)
❌ Slow to switch

Solution:

👉 Threads are lightweight and faster

⚙️ How It Works

Inside one process:

Process (Chrome)
 ├── Thread 1 → UI
 ├── Thread 2 → Network
 ├── Thread 3 → Rendering

All threads share:

memory

files

resources

But each has its own:

stack

registers

🔗 Connection to Programming

In Python:

import threading

def task():
    print("Running thread")

t = threading.Thread(target=task)
t.start()

👉 Multiple threads run inside one program.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Difference between process and thread?

👉 Process = heavy, separate memory
👉 Thread = lightweight, shared memory

🧠 Memory Trick
Process = separate house
Thread = roommates in same house
🧠 OS Concept 2: CPU Scheduling

Now the core of OS 🔥

1️⃣ Simple Idea

CPU scheduling =
👉 deciding which process gets CPU next

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Teacher in class 👨‍🏫

Students raise hands 🙋‍♂️

Teacher decides:

who answers first

who waits

That is scheduling.

⚙️ Why It Exists

Many processes want CPU:

P1, P2, P3, P4...

But CPU is limited.

So OS must choose:

👉 who runs next?

⚙️ Important Algorithms
1️⃣ FCFS (First Come First Serve)

👉 First process gets CPU first

P1 → P2 → P3

❌ Problem: slow if first process is big

2️⃣ SJF (Shortest Job First)

👉 Smallest job runs first

✔ Faster overall
❌ Hard to know job size

3️⃣ Round Robin (Most Important)

👉 Each process gets time slice

P1 → P2 → P3 → P1 → P2...

✔ Fair system
✔ Used in real OS

🔗 Connection to Context Switching

Every time CPU switches process:

👉 context switch happens

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why is Round Robin better than FCFS?

👉 Because it prevents starvation and gives fair CPU time.

🧠 Memory Trick
FCFS = queue
SJF = shortest first
RR = circular turn
⚙️ COA Concept 3: ALU (Arithmetic Logic Unit)
1️⃣ Simple Idea

ALU =
👉 part of CPU that performs calculations and logic operations

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Calculator 🧮

Whatever math you do → ALU does it in CPU.

⚙️ What ALU Does
Arithmetic
+  -  *  /
Logic
AND  OR  NOT  >
⚙️ Example
ADD R1 R2

ALU:

R1 + R2 → store result
🔗 Connection to Programming

In C:

int a = 5 + 3;

👉 ALU performs this operation internally.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What operations does ALU perform?

👉 Arithmetic and logical operations.

🧠 Memory Trick
ALU = All Logic & Arithmetic
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Instruction Formats
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Instruction format =
👉 structure of an instruction

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Think of a message format:

[Action] [Who] [Where]

Similarly CPU instruction:

[Opcode] [Operands]
⚙️ Components
1️⃣ Opcode

👉 what operation to perform

Example:

ADD, SUB, MOV
2️⃣ Operand

👉 data or location

Example:

R1, R2
⚙️ Types of Instruction Format
1️⃣ Zero Address
ADD

(stack based)

2️⃣ One Address
ADD X
3️⃣ Two Address
ADD R1, R2
4️⃣ Three Address
ADD R1, R2, R3
🔗 Connection to Addressing Modes (Day 2)

Instruction format tells:

👉 WHAT to do
Addressing mode tells:

👉 WHERE to get data

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is opcode?

👉 It specifies the operation to be performed.

🧠 Memory Trick
Instruction = Action + Data
